e Pandemic Perhaps tells the story of what happened when nothing really happened. Drawing on fieldwork among scientists and public health professionals in New York City, the book is an investigation of how actors and institutions produced a scene of extreme expectation through the circulation of dramatic plague visions. It argues that experts deployed these visions to draw attention to the possibility of a pandemic, frame the disease as a catastrophic event, and make it meaningful to the nation. Today, when we talk about pandemic influenza, we must always say “perhaps.” What, then, does it mean to engage a disease in the modality of the maybe?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEpidemicsxForecastingxUnited States. 0aEpidemicsxPreventionxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aEpidemicsxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aEpidemicsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEpidemicszUnited StatesxForecasting. 0aEpidemicszUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aInfluenzaxForecastingxUnited States. 0aInfluenzaxPreventionxUnited States. 0aInfluenzaxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aInfluenzaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aInfluenzazUnited StatesxForecasting. 0aInfluenzazUnited StatesxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095976740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959767/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles